y**](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/xaml/windows.ui.xaml.media.brush.opacity.aspx) is set to 0.5."},{"pos":[7566,7589],"content":"Linear gradient brushes"},{"content":"A <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>LinearGradientBrush<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR210108)</ept> paints an area with a gradient that's defined along a line.","pos":[7591,7736],"source":"A [**LinearGradientBrush**](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR210108) paints an area with a gradient that's defined along a line."},{"content":"This line is called the <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>gradient axis<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept>.","pos":[7737,7777],"source":" This line is called the *gradient axis*."},{"content":"You specify the gradient's colors and their locations along the gradient axis using <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>GradientStop<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR210078)</ept> objects.","pos":[7778,7947],"source":" You specify the gradient's colors and their locations along the gradient axis using [**GradientStop**](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR210078) objects."},{"content":"By default, the gradient axis runs from the upper left corner to the lower right corner of the area that the brush paints, resulting in a diagonal shading.","pos":[7948,8103]},{"content":"The <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>GradientStop<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR210078)</ept> is the basic building block of a gradient brush.","pos":[8105,8234],"source":"The [**GradientStop**](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR210078) is the basic building block of a gradient brush."},{"content":"A gradient stop specifies what the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Color<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/xaml/windows.ui.xaml.media.gradientstop.color.aspx)</ept> of the brush is at an <bpt id=\"p3\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p4\">**</bpt>Offset<ept id=\"p4\">**</ept><ept id=\"p3\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/xaml/windows.ui.xaml.media.gradientstop.offset.aspx)</ept> along the gradient axis, when the brush is applied to the area being painted.","pos":[8235,8595],"source":" A gradient stop specifies what the [**Color**](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/xaml/windows.ui.xaml.media.gradientstop.color.aspx) of the brush is at an [**Offset**](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/xaml/windows.ui.xaml.media.gradientstop.offset.aspx) along the gradient axis, when the brush is applied to the area being painted."},{"content":"The gradient stop's <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Color<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/xaml/windows.ui.xaml.media.gradientstop.color.aspx)</ept> property specifies the color of the gradient stop.","pos":[8597,8779],"source":"The gradient stop's [**Color**](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/xaml/windows.ui.xaml.media.gradientstop.color.aspx) property specifies the color of the gradient stop."},{"content":"You can set the color by using a predefined color name or by specifying the hexadecimal <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>ARGB<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> values.","pos":[8780,8884],"source":" You can set the color by using a predefined color name or by specifying the hexadecimal **ARGB** values."},{"content":"The <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Offset<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/xaml/windows.ui.xaml.media.gradientstop.offset.aspx)</ept> property of a <bpt id=\"p3\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p4\">**</bpt>GradientStop<ept id=\"p4\">**</ept><ept id=\"p3\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR210078)</ept> specifies the position of each <bpt id=\"p5\">**</bpt>GradientStop<ept id=\"p5\">**</ept> along the gradient axis.","pos":[8886,9167],"source":"The [**Offset**](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/xaml/windows.ui.xaml.media.gradientstop.offset.aspx) property of a [**GradientStop**](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR210078) specifies the position of each **GradientStop** along the gradient axis."},{"content":"The <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Offset<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> is a <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>double<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> that ranges from 0 to 1.","pos":[9168,9223],"source":" The **Offset** is a **double** that ranges from 0 to 1."},{"content":"An <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Offset<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> of 0 places the <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>GradientStop<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> at the start of the gradient axis, in other words near its <bpt id=\"p3\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p4\">**</bpt>StartPoint<ept id=\"p4\">**</ept><ept id=\"p3\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/xaml/windows.ui.xaml.media.lineargradientbrush.startpoint.aspx)</ept>.","pos":[9224,9459],"source":" An **Offset** of 0 places the **GradientStop** at the start of the gradient axis, in other words near its [**StartPoint**](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/xaml/windows.ui.xaml.media.lineargradientbrush.startpoint.aspx)."},{"content":"An <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Offset<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> of 1 places the <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>GradientStop<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> at the <bpt id=\"p3\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p4\">**</bpt>EndPoint<ept id=\"p4\">**</ept><ept id=\"p3\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/xaml/windows.ui.xaml.media.lineargradientbrush.endpoint.aspx)</ept>.","pos":[9460,9639],"source":" An **Offset** of 1 places the **GradientStop** at the [**EndPoint**](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/xaml/windows.ui.xaml.media.lineargradientbrush.endpoint.aspx)."},{"content":"At a minimum, a useful <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>LinearGradientBrush<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR210108)</ept> should have two <bpt id=\"p3\">**</bpt>GradientStop<ept id=\"p3\">**</ept> values, where each <bpt id=\"p4\">**</bpt>GradientStop<ept id=\"p4\">**</ept> should specify a different <bpt id=\"p5\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p6\">**</bpt>Color<ept id=\"p6\">**</ept><ept id=\"p5\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/xaml/windows.ui.xaml.media.gradientstop.color.aspx)</ept> and have a different <bpt id=\"p7\">**</bpt>Offset<ept id=\"p7\">**</ept> between 0 and 1.","pos":[9640,10003],"source":" At a minimum, a useful [**LinearGradientBrush**](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR210108) should have two **GradientStop** values, where each **GradientStop** should specify a different [**Color**](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/xaml/windows.ui.xaml.media.gradientstop.color.aspx) and have a different **Offset** between 0 and 1."},{"pos":[10005,10158],"content":"This example creates a linear gradient with four colors and uses it to paint a <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Rectangle<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR243371)</ept>.","source":"This example creates a linear gradient with four colors and uses it to paint a [**Rectangle**](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR243371)."},{"content":"The color of each point between gradient stops is linearly interpolated as a combination of the color specified by the two bounding gradient stops.","pos":[10742,10889]},{"content":"The illustration highlights the gradient stops in the previous example.","pos":[10890,10961]},{"content":"The circles mark the position of the gradient stops, and the dashed line shows the gradient axis.","pos":[10962,11059]},{"content":"Gradient stops<ph id=\"ph1\">](images/linear-gradients-stops.png)</ph> You can change the line at which the gradient stops are positioned by setting the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>StartPoint<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/xaml/windows.ui.xaml.media.lineargradientbrush.startpoint.aspx)</ept> and <bpt id=\"p3\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p4\">**</bpt>EndPoint<ept id=\"p4\">**</ept><ept id=\"p3\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/xaml/windows.ui.xaml.media.lineargradientbrush.endpoint.aspx)</ept> properties to be different values than the <ph id=\"ph2\">`(0,0)`</ph> and <ph id=\"ph3\">`(1,1)`</ph> starting defaults.","pos":[11063,11535],"source":"Gradient stops](images/linear-gradients-stops.png)\nYou can change the line at which the gradient stops are positioned by setting the [**StartPoint**](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/xaml/windows.ui.xaml.media.lineargradientbrush.startpoint.aspx) and [**EndPoint**](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/xaml/windows.ui.xaml.media.lineargradientbrush.endpoint.aspx) properties to be different values than the `(0,0)` and `(1,1)` starting defaults."},{"content":"By changing the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>StartPoint<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> and <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>EndPoint<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> coordinate values, you can create horizontal or vertical gradients, reverse the gradient direction, or condense the gradient spread to apply to a smaller range than the full painted area.","pos":[11536,11771],"source":" By changing the **StartPoint** and **EndPoint** coordinate values, you can create horizontal or vertical gradients, reverse the gradient direction, or condense the gradient spread to apply to a smaller range than the full painted area."},{"content":"To condense the gradient, you set values of <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>StartPoint<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> and/or <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>EndPoint<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> to be something that is between the values 0 and 1.","pos":[11772,11902],"source":" To condense the gradient, you set values of **StartPoint** and/or **EndPoint** to be something that is between the values 0 and 1."},{"content":"For example, if you want a horizontal gradient where the fade all happens on the left half of the brush and the right side is solid to your last <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>GradientStop<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR210078)</ept> color, you specify a <bpt id=\"p3\">**</bpt>StartPoint<ept id=\"p3\">**</ept> of <ph id=\"ph1\">`(0,0)`</ph> and an <bpt id=\"p4\">**</bpt>EndPoint<ept id=\"p4\">**</ept> of <ph id=\"ph2\">`(0.5,0)`</ph>.","pos":[11903,12205],"source":" For example, if you want a horizontal gradient where the fade all happens on the left half of the brush and the right side is solid to your last [**GradientStop**](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR210078) color, you specify a **StartPoint** of `(0,0)` and an **EndPoint** of `(0.5,0)`."},{"pos":[12349,12376],"content":"Use tools to make gradients"},{"content":"Now that you know how linear gradients work, you can use Visual Studio or Blend to make creating these gradients easier.","pos":[12378,12498]},{"content":"To create a gradient, select the object you want to apply a gradient to on the design surface or in XAML view.","pos":[12499,12609]},{"content":"Expand <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Brush<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> and select the <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Linear Gradient<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> tab (see next screenshot).","pos":[12610,12688],"source":" Expand **Brush** and select the **Linear Gradient** tab (see next screenshot)."},{"content":"Create linear gradient using Visual Studio.","pos":[12692,12735]},{"content":"Now you can change the colors of the gradient stops and slide their positions using the bar on the bottom.","pos":[12772,12878]},{"content":"You can also add new gradient stops by clicking on the bar and remove them by dragging the stops off of the bar (see next screenshot).","pos":[12879,13013]},{"content":"Bar at bottom of properties window that controls gradient stops.","pos":[13017,13081]},{"pos":[13217,13230],"content":"Image brushes"},{"content":"An <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>ImageBrush<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR210101)</ept> paints an area with an image, with the image to paint coming from an image file source.","pos":[13232,13397],"source":"An [**ImageBrush**](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR210101) paints an area with an image, with the image to paint coming from an image file source."},{"content":"You set the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>ImageSource<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR210107)</ept> property with the path of the image to load.","pos":[13398,13530],"source":" You set the [**ImageSource**](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR210107) property with the path of the image to load."},{"content":"Typically, the image source comes from a <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Content<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> item that is part of your app's resources.","pos":[13531,13626],"source":" Typically, the image source comes from a **Content** item that is part of your app's resources."},{"content":"By default, an <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>ImageBrush<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR210101)</ept> stretches its image to completely fill the painted area, possibly distorting the image if the painted area has a different aspect ratio than the image.","pos":[13628,13869],"source":"By default, an [**ImageBrush**](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR210101) stretches its image to completely fill the painted area, possibly distorting the image if the painted area has a different aspect ratio than the image."},{"content":"You can change this behavior by changing the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Stretch<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR242975)</ept> property from its default value of <bpt id=\"p3\">**</bpt>Fill<ept id=\"p3\">**</ept> and setting it as <bpt id=\"p4\">**</bpt>None<ept id=\"p4\">**</ept>, <bpt id=\"p5\">**</bpt>Uniform<ept id=\"p5\">**</ept>, or <bpt id=\"p6\">**</bpt>UniformToFill<ept id=\"p6\">**</ept>.","pos":[13870,14093],"source":" You can change this behavior by changing the [**Stretch**](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR242975) property from its default value of **Fill** and setting it as **None**, **Uniform**, or **UniformToFill**."},{"content":"The next example creates an <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>ImageBrush<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR210101)</ept> and sets the <bpt id=\"p3\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p4\">**</bpt>ImageSource<ept id=\"p4\">**</ept><ept id=\"p3\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR210107)</ept> to an image named licorice.jpg, which you must include as a resource in the app.","pos":[14095,14367],"source":"The next example creates an [**ImageBrush**](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR210101) and sets the [**ImageSource**](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR210107) to an image named licorice.jpg, which you must include as a resource in the app."},{"content":"The <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>ImageBrush<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> then paints the area defined by an <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p3\">**</bpt>Ellipse<ept id=\"p3\">**</ept><ept id=\"p2\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR243343)</ept> shape.","pos":[14368,14500],"source":" The **ImageBrush** then paints the area defined by an [**Ellipse**](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR243343) shape."},{"pos":[14644,14755],"content":"Here's what the rendered <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>ImageBrush<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR210101)</ept> looks like.","source":"Here's what the rendered [**ImageBrush**](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR210101) looks like."},{"content":"A rendered ImageBrush.","pos":[14759,14781]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>ImageBrush<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR210101)</ept> and <bpt id=\"p3\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p4\">**</bpt>Image<ept id=\"p4\">**</ept><ept id=\"p3\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR242752)</ept> both reference an image source file by Uniform Resource Identifier (URI), where that image source file uses several possible image formats.","pos":[14815,15103],"source":"[**ImageBrush**](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR210101) and [**Image**](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR242752) both reference an image source file by Uniform Resource Identifier (URI), where that image source file uses several possible image formats."},{"content":"These image source files are specified as URIs.","pos":[15104,15151]},{"content":"For more info about specifying image sources, the usable image formats, and packaging them in an app, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Image and ImageBrush<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/Mt280382)</ept>.","pos":[15152,15339],"source":" For more info about specifying image sources, the usable image formats, and packaging them in an app, see [Image and ImageBrush](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/Mt280382)."},{"content":"Brushes and text","pos":[15344,15360]},{"content":"You can also use brushes to apply rendering characteristics to text elements.","pos":[15362,15439]},{"content":"For example, the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Foreground<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR209665)</ept> property of <bpt id=\"p3\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p4\">**</bpt>TextBlock<ept id=\"p4\">**</ept><ept id=\"p3\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR209652)</ept> takes a <bpt id=\"p5\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p6\">**</bpt>Brush<ept id=\"p6\">**</ept><ept id=\"p5\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR228076)</ept>.","pos":[15440,15696],"source":" For example, the [**Foreground**](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR209665) property of [**TextBlock**](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR209652) takes a [**Brush**](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR228076)."},{"content":"You can apply any of the brushes described here to text.","pos":[15697,15753]},{"content":"But be careful with brushes applied to text, because it's possible to make the text unreadable if you use brushes that bleed into whatever background the text is rendered on top of, or that distract from the outlines of text characters.","pos":[15754,15990]},{"content":"Use <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>SolidColorBrush<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR242962)</ept> for readability of text elements in most cases, unless you want the text element to be mostly decorative.","pos":[15991,16180],"source":" Use [**SolidColorBrush**](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR242962) for readability of text elements in most cases, unless you want the text element to be mostly decorative."},{"content":"Even when you use a solid color, make sure that the text color you choose has enough contrast against the background color of the text's layout container.","pos":[16182,16336]},{"content":"The level of contrast between text foreground and text container background is an accessibility consideration.","pos":[16337,16447]},{"content":"WebViewBrush","pos":[16452,16464]},{"content":"A <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>WebViewBrush<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR227703)</ept> is a special type of brush that can access the content normally viewed in a <bpt id=\"p3\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p4\">**</bpt>WebView<ept id=\"p4\">**</ept><ept id=\"p3\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR227702)</ept> control.","pos":[16466,16701],"source":"A [**WebViewBrush**](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR227703) is a special type of brush that can access the content normally viewed in a [**WebView**](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR227702) control."},{"content":"Instead of rendering the content in the rectangular <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>WebView<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> control area, <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>WebViewBrush<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> paints that content onto another element that has a <bpt id=\"p3\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p4\">**</bpt>Brush<ept id=\"p4\">**</ept><ept id=\"p3\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR228076)</ept>-type property for a render surface.","pos":[16702,16954],"source":" Instead of rendering the content in the rectangular **WebView** control area, **WebViewBrush** paints that content onto another element that has a [**Brush**](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR228076)-type property for a render surface."},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>WebViewBrush<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> isn't appropriate for every brush scenario, but is useful for transitions of a <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>WebView<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept>.","pos":[16955,17063],"source":"**WebViewBrush** isn't appropriate for every brush scenario, but is useful for transitions of a **WebView**."},{"content":"For more info, see <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>WebViewBrush<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.","pos":[17064,17100],"source":" For more info, see **WebViewBrush**."},{"content":"Brushes as XAML resources","pos":[17105,17130]},{"content":"You can declare any brush to be a keyed XAML resource in a XAML resource dictionary.","pos":[17132,17216]},{"content":"This makes it easy to replicate the same brush values as applied to multiple elements in a UI.","pos":[17217,17311]},{"content":"The brush values are then shared and applied to any case where you reference the brush resource as a <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>{StaticResource}<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/Mt185588)</ept> usage in your XAML.","pos":[17312,17509],"source":" The brush values are then shared and applied to any case where you reference the brush resource as a [{StaticResource}](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/Mt185588) usage in your XAML."},{"content":"This includes cases where you have a XAML control template that references the shared brush, and the control template is itself a keyed XAML resource.","pos":[17510,17660]},{"content":"Brushes in code","pos":[17665,17680]},{"content":"It's much more typical to specify brushes using XAML than it is to use code to define brushes.","pos":[17682,17776]},{"content":"This is because brushes are usually defined as XAML resources, and because brush values are often the output of design tools or otherwise as part of a XAML UI definition.","pos":[17777,17947]},{"content":"Still, for the occasional case where you might want to define a brush using code, all the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Brush<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR228076)</ept> types are available for code instantiation.","pos":[17948,18151],"source":" Still, for the occasional case where you might want to define a brush using code, all the [**Brush**](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR228076) types are available for code instantiation."},{"content":"To create a <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>SolidColorBrush<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR242962)</ept> in code, use the constructor that takes a <bpt id=\"p3\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p4\">**</bpt>Color<ept id=\"p4\">**</ept><ept id=\"p3\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/Hh673723)</ept> parameter.","pos":[18153,18367],"source":"To create a [**SolidColorBrush**](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/wi